SIMPLE: heave
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Heave
<hw>Heave</hw> <pr>(h⟦emac⟧v)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Heaved</conjf> <pr>(h⟦emac⟧vd)</pr>, or
<conjf>Hove</conjf> <pr>(h⟦omac⟧v)</pr>; <pos>p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Heaved</conjf>, <conjf>Hove</conjf>, formerly
<conjf>Hoven</conjf> <pr>(h⟦omac⟧"v'n)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Heaving</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>heven</ets>,
<ets>hebben</ets>, AS. <ets>hebban</ets>; akin to OS.
<ets>hebbian</ets>, D. <ets>heffen</ets>, OHG. <ets>heffan</ets>,
<ets>hevan</ets>, G. <ets>heben</ets>, Icel. <ets>hefja</ets>, Sw.
<ets>h⟦aum⟧fva</ets>, Dan. <ets>h⟦ae⟧ve</ets>, Goth. <ets>hafjan</ets>,
L. <ets>capere</ets> to take, seize; cf. Gr. <grk>kw`ph</grk> handle.
Cf. <er>Accept</er>, <er>Behoof</er>, <er>Capacious</er>,
<er>Forceps</er>, <er>Haft</er>, <er>Receipt</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To cause to move upward or onward by a lifting effort; to lift; to
raise; to hoist; -- often with <xex>up</xex>; <as>as, the wave
<ex>heaved</ex> the boat on land</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One <qex>heaved</qex> ahigh, to be hurled down below.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Heave</xex>, as now used, implies that the thing
raised is heavy or hard to move; but formerly it was used in a less
restricted sense.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Here a little child I stand,⟦br⟧
<qex>Heaving</qex> up my either hand.</q>
<rj><qau>Herrick.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To throw; to cast; -- obsolete, provincial, or
colloquial, except in certain nautical phrases; <as>as, to
<ex>heave</ex> the lead; to <ex>heave</ex> the log.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To force from, or into, any position; to cause to
move; also, to throw off; -- mostly used in certain nautical phrases;
<as>as, to <ex>heave</ex> the ship ahead</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To raise or force from the breast; to utter with
effort; <as>as, to <ex>heave</ex> a sigh</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The wretched animal <qex>heaved</qex> forth such groans.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To cause to swell or rise, as the breast or
bosom.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The glittering, finny swarms⟦br⟧
That <qex>heave</qex> our friths, and crowd upon our shores.</q>
<rj><qau>Thomson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To heave a cable short</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>,
<cd>to haul in cable till the ship is almost perpendicularly above the
anchor.</cd> -- <col><b>To heave a ship ahead</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to warp her ahead when not under sail, as by
means of cables.</cd> -- <col><b>To heave a ship down</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to throw or lay her down on one side; to careen
her.</cd> -- <col><b>To heave a ship to</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>,
<cd>to bring the ship's head to the wind, and stop her motion.</cd> --
<col><b>To heave about</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to put about
suddenly.</cd> -- <col><b>To heave in</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>,
<cd>to shorten (cable).</cd> -- <col><b>To heave in stays</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to put a vessel on the other tack.</cd> --
<col><b>To heave out a sail</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to unfurl
it.</cd> -- <col><b>To heave taut</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to
turn a capstan, etc., till the rope becomes strained. See <er>Taut</er>,
and <er>Tight</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>To heave the lead</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to take soundings with lead and line.</cd> --
<col><b>To heave the log</b></col>. <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <cd>See
<er>Log</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>To heave up anchor</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to raise it from the bottom of the sea or
elsewhere.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 680 --></p>

<p><ent>Heave</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Heave
<hw>Heave</hw> <pr>(h⟦emac⟧v)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
be thrown up or raised; to rise upward, as a tower or mound.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And the huge columns <qex>heave</qex> into the sky.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where <qex>heaves</qex> the turf in many a moldering heap.</q>
<rj><qau>Gray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>heaving</qex> sods of Bunker Hill.</q> <rj><qau>E.
Everett.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To rise and fall with alternate motions, as the
lungs in heavy breathing, as waves in a heavy sea, as ships on the
billows, as the earth when broken up by frost, etc.; to swell; to
dilate; to expand; to distend; hence, to labor; to struggle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Frequent for breath his panting bosom <qex>heaves</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>heaving</qex> plain of ocean.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make an effort to raise, throw, or move anything;
to strain to do something difficult.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Church of England had struggled and <qex>heaved</qex> at a
reformation ever since Wyclif's days.</q>
<rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To make an effort to vomit; to retch; to
vomit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To heave at</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To make an effort
at.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To attack, to oppose.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<au>Fuller.</au> -- <col><b>To heave in sight</b></col> <cd>(as a ship
at sea), to come in sight; to appear.</cd> -- <col><b>To heave
up</b></col>, <cd>to vomit.</cd> <mark>[Low]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Heave</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Heave
<hw>Heave</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An effort to raise
something, as a weight, or one's self, or to move something
heavy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>After many strains and <qex>heaves</qex>⟦br⟧
He got up to his saddle eaves.</q> <rj><qau>Hudibras.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An upward motion; a rising; a swell or distention,
as of the breast in difficult breathing, of the waves, of the earth in
an earthquake, and the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There's matter in these sighs, these profound
<qex>heaves</qex>,⟦br⟧
You must translate.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>None could guess whether the next <qex>heave</qex> of the
earthquake would settle . . . or swallow them.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>A horizontal dislocation in a
metallic lode, taking place at an intersection with another
lode.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Heaven</ent>⟦br⟧
